<Link id="l00484" /><CodeLine lineNumber="484"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Returns true iff the routine could find two commutable operands in the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00485" /><CodeLine lineNumber="485"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// given machine instruction.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00486" /><CodeLine lineNumber="486"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// The &#39;SrcOpIdx1&#39; and &#39;SrcOpIdx2&#39; are INPUT and OUTPUT arguments.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00487" /><CodeLine lineNumber="487"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// If any of the INPUT values is set to the special value</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00495" /><CodeLine lineNumber="495"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00496" /><CodeLine lineNumber="496"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// For example, calling this method this way:</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00634" /><CodeLine lineNumber="634"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Analyze the branching code at the end of MBB, returning</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00635" /><CodeLine lineNumber="635"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// true if it cannot be understood (e.g. it&#39;s a switch dispatch or isn&#39;t</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00636" /><CodeLine lineNumber="636"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// implemented for a target).  Upon success, this returns false and returns</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00637" /><CodeLine lineNumber="637"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// with the following information in various cases:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00638" /><CodeLine lineNumber="638"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00639" /><CodeLine lineNumber="639"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// 1 If this block ends with no branches (it just falls through to its succ)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00640" /><CodeLine lineNumber="640"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    just return false, leaving TBB/FBB null.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00641" /><CodeLine lineNumber="641"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// 2 If this block ends with only an unconditional branch, it sets TBB to be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00642" /><CodeLine lineNumber="642"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    the destination block.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00643" /><CodeLine lineNumber="643"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// 3 If this block ends with a conditional branch and it falls through to a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00644" /><CodeLine lineNumber="644"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    successor block, it sets TBB to be the branch destination block and a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00645" /><CodeLine lineNumber="645"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    list of operands that evaluate the condition. These operands can be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00646" /><CodeLine lineNumber="646"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    passed to other TargetInstrInfo methods to create new branches.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00647" /><CodeLine lineNumber="647"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// 4 If this block ends with a conditional branch followed by an</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00648" /><CodeLine lineNumber="648"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    unconditional branch, it returns the &#39;true&#39; destination in TBB, the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00649" /><CodeLine lineNumber="649"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    &#39;false&#39; destination in FBB, and a list of operands that evaluate the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00650" /><CodeLine lineNumber="650"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    condition.  These operands can be passed to other TargetInstrInfo</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00651" /><CodeLine lineNumber="651"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    methods to create new branches.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00652" /><CodeLine lineNumber="652"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00653" /><CodeLine lineNumber="653"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Note that removeBranch and insertBranch must be implemented to support</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00654" /><CodeLine lineNumber="654"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// cases where this method returns success.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00655" /><CodeLine lineNumber="655"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00656" /><CodeLine lineNumber="656"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// If AllowModify is true, then this routine is allowed to modify the basic</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00657" /><CodeLine lineNumber="657"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// block (e.g. delete instructions after the unconditional branch).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00658" /><CodeLine lineNumber="658"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01849" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1849"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Return the current execution domain and bit mask of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01850" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1850"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// possible domains for instruction.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01851" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1851"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01852" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1852"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Some micro-architectures have multiple execution domains, and multiple</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01853" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1853"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// opcodes that perform the same operation in different domains.  For</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01854" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1854"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// example, the x86 architecture provides the por, orps, and orpd</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01855" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1855"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// instructions that all do the same thing.  There is a latency penalty if a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01856" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1856"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// register is written in one domain and read in another.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01857" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1857"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01858" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1858"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// This function returns a pair (domain, mask) containing the execution</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01859" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1859"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// domain of MI, and a bit mask of possible domains.  The setExecutionDomain</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01860" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1860"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// function can be used to change the opcode to one of the domains in the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01861" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1861"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// bit mask.  Instructions whose execution domain can&#39;t be changed should</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01862" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1862"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// return a 0 mask.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01863" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1863"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01864" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1864"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// The execution domain numbers don&#39;t have any special meaning except domain</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01865" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1865"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// 0 is used for instructions that are not associated with any interesting</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01866" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1866"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// execution domain.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01867" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1867"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01879" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1879"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Returns the preferred minimum clearance</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01880" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1880"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// before an instruction with an unwanted partial register update.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01881" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1881"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01882" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1882"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Some instructions only write part of a register, and implicitly need to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01883" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1883"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// read the other parts of the register.  This may cause unwanted stalls</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01884" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1884"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// preventing otherwise unrelated instructions from executing in parallel in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01885" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1885"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// an out-of-order CPU.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01886" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1886"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01887" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1887"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// For example, the x86 instruction cvtsi2ss writes its result to bits</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01888" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1888"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// &#91;31:0&#93; of the destination xmm register. Bits &#91;127:32&#93; are unaffected, so</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01889" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1889"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// the instruction needs to wait for the old value of the register to become</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01890" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1890"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// available:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01891" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1891"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01892" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1892"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   addps %xmm1, %xmm0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01893" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1893"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   movaps %xmm0, (%rax)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01894" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1894"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   cvtsi2ss %rbx, %xmm0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01895" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1895"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01896" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1896"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// In the code above, the cvtsi2ss instruction needs to wait for the addps</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01897" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1897"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// instruction before it can issue, even though the high bits of %xmm0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01898" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1898"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// probably aren&#39;t needed.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01899" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1899"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01900" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1900"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// This hook returns the preferred clearance before MI, measured in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01901" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1901"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// instructions.  Other defs of MI&#39;s operand OpNum are avoided in the last N</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01902" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1902"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// instructions before MI.  It should only return a positive value for</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01903" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1903"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// unwanted dependencies.  If the old bits of the defined register have</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01904" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1904"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// useful values, or if MI is determined to otherwise read the dependency,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01905" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1905"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// the hook should return 0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01906" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1906"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01907" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1907"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// The unwanted dependency may be handled by:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01908" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1908"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01909" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1909"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// 1 Allocating the same register for an MI def and use.  That makes the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01910" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1910"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    unwanted dependency identical to a required dependency.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01911" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1911"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01912" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1912"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// 2 Allocating a register for the def that has no defs in the previous N</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01913" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1913"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    instructions.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01914" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1914"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01915" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1915"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// 3 Calling breakPartialRegDependency() with the same arguments.  This</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01916" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1916"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///    allows the target to insert a dependency breaking instruction.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01917" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1917"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01918" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1918"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">virtual</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">unsigned</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01919" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1919" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targetinstrinfo/#a14308e147ea57526f7fd1198ab551a9a"><span class="doxyHighlight">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targetinstrinfo/#a14308e147ea57526f7fd1198ab551a9a">getPartialRegUpdateClearance</a>(</span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">const</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/machineinstr">MachineInstr</a> &amp;<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/codegen/lib/codegen/globalisel/irtranslator-cpp/#abe44dfdea65b4f7e11e0a608ab708b76">MI</a>, </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">unsigned</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> OpNum,</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l02001" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2001"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// instructions with more than one memory operands, the alias check on a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02002" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2002"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// single MachineInstr pair has quadratic overhead and results in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02003" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2003"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// unacceptable performance in the worst case. The limit here is to clamp</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02004" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2004"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// that maximal checks performed. Usually, that&#39;s the product of memory</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02005" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2005"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// operand numbers from that pair of MachineInstr to be checked. For</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02006" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2006"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// instance, with two MachineInstrs with 4 and 5 memory operands</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02007" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2007"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// correspondingly, a total of 20 checks are required. With this limit set to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02008" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2008"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// 16, their alias check is skipped. We choose to limit the product instead</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02009" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2009"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// of the individual instruction as targets may have special MachineInstrs</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02010" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2010"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// with a considerably high number of memory operands, such as &#96;ldm&#96; in ARM.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02011" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2011"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Setting this limit per MachineInstr would result in either too high</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02012" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2012"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// overhead or too rigid restriction.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02013" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2013" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targetinstrinfo/#a6f67bce035b491e5e6d95286ffe20da1"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">virtual</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">unsigned</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targetinstrinfo/#a6f67bce035b491e5e6d95286ffe20da1">getMemOperandAACheckLimit</a>()</span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword"> const </span><span class="doxyHighlight">&#123; </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordFlow">return</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> 16; &#125;</span></CodeLine>
